The effect of different concentrations of Cr(VI) on the fluorescence intensity of the N, P-CDs was evaluated under the optimized conditions. The nanoprobes' fluorescence intensity was severely decreased through the quenching process, as the concentration of Cr(VI) was increased (Fig. 4
                        ). The quenching ratio was found to vary linearly with the Cr(VI) concentrations in the 0.05 to 3 µM (2.6–156 μg L−1 in Cr) interval, where the equation of the linear fit was F
                        0/F = 2.91(±0.02) × C
                        Cr(VI) + 0.90(±0.01), r = 0.9995 (n = 14). The relative standard deviation of ten (n = 10) independent measurements of Cr(VI) 0.5 µM solution was calculated as 2.33%, indicating good precision of the method. The LOD was found to be 26 nM (1.3 μg L−1 in Cr), which is far below the guidelines values set by the WHO (50 µg L−1), the United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA; 100 µg L−1), and the CONAMA (Brazil; 50 µg L−1) for Cr(VI) in drinking water [23]. The method's analytical parameters were compared with reported data related to fluorescence sensing of Cr(VI) using carbon dots (Table 2
                        ), highlighting its better sensitivity and lower LOD.
